reviewText: Purchasing this CD lens cleaner was my last resort before scouring junk yards to replace the CD/radio in my 2011 RAV4. However, had I not read reviews written by other Amazon customers, I would have become frustrated and given up. Patience is key! At first, my CD player wouldn't even accept the lens cleaner CD, but pressing the AUX button, turning the unit on and off, and switching between the radio and CD functionalities worked. Once inserted, I ran the lens cleaner CD through the process several times. Even then, music CDs would work only a few times before the issue would return and my music CDs would either not load or not play. Each time the issue resurfaced, I used the lens CD to repeat the cleaning process. It's been nearly a month since I've experienced any issues. WORD TO THE WISE: Don't leave CDs hanging out of your player. I travel with a dog and in hindsight realize my laziness resulted in dander, dust and fine hairs traveling through the air, onto CDs and into the unit. reviewText: Used on a year old Bose Wave IV single CD system that was occasionally skipping and it resolved the issue after one use.  We live in a high wind, high dust area and I suspect that had I tried this CD lens cleaner on our older Bose Wave II, I'd not have had to replace it.  Just pop the CD into the player with the label up and listen to the approximate 30 seconds of verbal instruction and music.  When the music stops, advance to track 3 and the same voice will soon tell you that cleaning is complete.  You can either continue listening to the music on the disc or remove the disc at this point.  We heard a small amount of soft whirring and clicking during the entire process which lasted less than a minute. Note that when removing the disc, you want to avoid handling the underside of the disc as the two tiny microfibre brushes located there will pick up oil and debris from your hands.  Store the disc in its jewel case and away from any extreme temperature and high humidity areas to keep it clean and functional; it should last years.

reviewText: It works. My 10 year old, high-end, multi-disk CD player is now functioning normally without skipping. The cleaning brushes are positioned at track two on the disk. DON'T TOUCH THEM or you will smash them!!! If you just want to quickly clean the laser lens without listening to the other information, simply place the disk in the player's disk tray with the printed side up. There are two metal surfaces on the disk which you can touch to discharge static electricity. Then play track two with your speaker system on. You will hear several beeps... done. The remainder of the disk is verbal instruction for system testing to check for speaker function, balance and polarity, Yes, it takes only seconds for the lens to be cleaned. The CD spins at about 500 rpm and there are 8 brushes at the track 2 position. So you don't need to go nuts and run the track repeatedly. If your kid put a pancake in the player, this isn't going to fix it anyway! Ditto these instructions for your DVD player. I have no idea if this will work for a player that draws the disk in through a slot. I seems as though that might smash the brushes.
title: Allsop Ultra ProLens Cleaner for DVD, CD Drives, and Game Players (23321)
